/*
Problem: 153. Find Minimum in Rotated Sorted Array

Approach:
1. If the array is already sorted, return the first element.
2. Use Binary Search to locate the peak (maximum element). PEAK ELEMENT
3. The element immediately after the peak is the minimum.
4. If nums[mid] > nums[mid + 1], then nums[mid + 1] is the answer.
5. Otherwise:
   - If nums[mid] belongs to the left sorted half,
     move right.
   - Else, move left.

Time Complexity: O(log n)
Space Complexity: O(1)
*/

class Solution {
public:
    int findMin(vector<int>& nums) {

        int n = nums.size();

        // Array is already sorted
        if (nums[0] <= nums[n - 1])
            return nums[0];

        int st = 0;
        int end = n - 1;

        while (st <= end) {

            int mid = st + (end - st) / 2;

            // Peak found
            if (mid < n - 1 && nums[mid] > nums[mid + 1])
                return nums[mid + 1];

            // Peak lies on the right
            if (nums[mid] >= nums[st]) {
                st = mid + 1;
            }

            // Peak lies on the left
            else {
                end = mid - 1;
            }
        }

        return -1;
    }
};

/*
==========================================
My Misconceptions / Learnings
==========================================

1. I first tried finding the minimum directly.

Then I realized another way is to first find the
peak (maximum element), because the minimum is
always the element just after the peak.

------------------------------------------

2. Why do we first check if the array is sorted?

Example:

0 1 2 3 4

There is no rotation, so there is no peak.
The first element itself is the minimum.

------------------------------------------

3. Why only check:

nums[mid] > nums[mid + 1]

and not

nums[mid] > nums[mid - 1] ?

Because in a rotated sorted array with unique
elements, the only place where an element is
greater than its next element is the rotation point
(the peak).

So checking the next element is sufficient.

------------------------------------------

4. Why do we write:

mid < n - 1

Before accessing nums[mid + 1]?

To avoid going out of bounds when mid is the
last index.

------------------------------------------

5. How do we decide which side to search?

If

nums[mid] >= nums[st]

then mid lies in the left sorted part, so the
peak must be at mid or on its right.

Otherwise, mid lies in the right sorted part,
so the peak must be on the left.

------------------------------------------

6. Complexity

Time Complexity: O(log n)

Space Complexity: O(1)

------------------------------------------

Note:

The standard solution compares nums[mid] with
nums[end] and directly searches for the minimum.

This peak-based approach is also O(log n), but
requires a few more edge-case checks.
*/
